  "market_context": "NASDAQ 100 E-mini Futures on the 5-minute chart. Price was in a premium of the displacement range with equal lows resting below as sell-side liquidity. Buy-side liquidity above had already been swept, followed by an aggressive move down forming a high-low-higher-high structure.",
  "key_observation": "After the sellside sweep and aggressive move up, a breaker block formed with a nested fair value gap inside it. The breaker block defines the wider entry zone while the nested FVG provides a tighter, higher RR entry into the same PD array confluence.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identify the buy side liquidity that was taken and note the aggressive displacement move off of it",
    "Map out the structure showing a high, low, higher high — confirming a breaker block setup",
    "Locate the breaker block on the 5-minute chart as the primary PD array",
    "Identify the nested fair value gap resting inside the breaker block as a tighter entry zone",
    "Define two entry options: a wider entry at the breaker block, or a tighter entry at the fair value gap",
    "Set stop loss below the swing low and target the equal lows below for partials",
    "Confirm checklist: stop raid, market structure shift, return to premium with PD array confluence, solid risk-to-reward"
  ],
  "outcome": "Price returned to the breaker block / fair value gap zone, then expanded lower and reached the equal lows below for partial profit.",
  "lessons": "When a breaker block contains a nested fair value gap, both serve as valid PD arrays. The trader can balance fill probability (wider breaker entry) against risk-to-reward (tighter FVG entry) based on what catches their eye and the checklist confluence.",
